WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.320
We trust algorithms to make fair decisions about who gets a job or extra help in school.

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:11.040
So how does an objective machine develop algorithmic bias?

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:17.120
Take a community college, using a model to predict which incoming students need targeted support.

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:22.000
To work, this algorithm first has to learn what success looks like.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.760
It ingests years of historical data, finding patterns in past grades and enrollment.

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:33.440
But there's a hidden flaw in those records. Due to long-standing societal inequities,

00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:37.840
marginalized groups often show lower historical success rates in these systems.

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:42.000
The algorithm can't see the societal context behind those numbers.

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:46.640
It just turns that historical inequality into a rigid rule,

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:50.000
equating the historically dominant group with the ideal baseline.

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:54.480
Turning past disparities into mathematical rules for the future

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:56.960
is exactly how algorithmic bias operates.

00:00:57.680 --> 00:01:00.800
What happens when this model evaluates a new cohort?

00:01:00.800 --> 00:01:06.000
By applying that flawed baseline, the model quietly underestimates Black students.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.760
It incorrectly predicts they are more likely to succeed than they actually are.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:16.640
As a result, they receive fewer resources than peers with the exact same actual level of need.

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:19.200
And that incoming community college student?

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:23.760
The algorithm quietly locks the gate, denying them support based on historical

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:33.280
disparities they had no part in.
